\pard\b\fs27 1. Introduction\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard This project, **Farmer-Buyer Marketplace System**, was developed as an undergraduate Java project to demonstrate both **core Java programming** and **Object-Oriented Programming concepts** in a practical and meaningful way.\par
\pard \par
\pard The main idea behind the project is simple and socially relevant: farmers often have crops available for sale, while buyers are looking for crops within a certain budget and location. This system acts like a digital bridge between the two. It stores farmer and buyer information, compares their needs and offerings, and recommends the best matches based on:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? crop availability\par
\pard\li720 ? budget compatibility\par
\pard\li720 ? same-city proximity\par
\pard\li720 ? quantity closeness\par
\pard \par
\pard The project was intentionally designed to be **academic, understandable, and presentable**. Instead of making it overly complicated, the system focuses on clearly demonstrating syllabus topics through a realistic application.\par
\pard \par
\pard This project now supports:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? a **Java Swing desktop application**\par
\pard\li720 ? a **browser-based web version**\par
\pard\li720 ? **CSV file storage**\par
\pard\li720 ? **serialized backup**\par
\pard\li720 ? **UML documentation**\par
\pard \par
\pard So it is both technically complete and strong from a report/viva point of view.\par
\pard \par
\par
\pard \par
\pard\b\fs27 2. Problem Statement\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard Farmers and buyers usually depend on middlemen, manual communication, or scattered marketplaces. Because of this, it can be difficult for:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? farmers to find the right buyers\par
\pard\li720 ? buyers to locate suitable sellers quickly\par
\pard\li720 ? both parties to compare crop type, budget, and location efficiently\par
\pard \par
\pard This project solves that problem by creating a small marketplace system that:\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. stores farmer details\par
\pard 2. stores buyer requirements\par
\pard 3. compares both sets of data\par
\pard 4. generates suitable recommendations\par
\pard 5. saves and loads data from files\par
\pard \par
\par
\pard \par
\pard\b\fs27 3. Objectives of the Project\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard The main objectives of this project are:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? to build a meaningful Java application based on a real-world idea\par
\pard\li720 ? to cover the full undergraduate Java syllabus in one project\par
\pard\li720 ? to show clear use of OOP concepts like inheritance, abstraction, interfaces, and polymorphism\par
\pard\li720 ? to demonstrate file handling, exception handling, and data persistence\par
\pard\li720 ? to provide an easy-to-use interface for demonstration and evaluation\par
\pard \par
\par
\pard \par
