\pard\b\fs27 6. Project Workflow\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard This section explains the workflow in human terms.\par
\pard \par
\pard\b 6.1 Farmer workflow\b0\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. A user opens the Farmer section.\par
\pard 2. The user enters:\par
\pard    - farmer ID\par
\pard    - name\par
\pard    - city\par
\pard    - phone\par
\pard    - crop type\par
\pard    - quantity available\par
\pard    - price per unit\par
\pard 3. The UI creates a `Farmer` object.\par
\pard 4. The object is validated through constructors and setters.\par
\pard 5. The manager checks whether the ID is unique.\par
\pard 6. If valid, the farmer is added to the system.\par
\pard 7. The table refreshes and shows the new farmer.\par
\pard \par
\pard\b 6.2 Buyer workflow\b0\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. A user opens the Buyer section.\par
\pard 2. The user enters:\par
\pard    - buyer ID\par
\pard    - name\par
\pard    - city\par
\pard    - phone\par
\pard    - required crop\par
\pard    - required quantity\par
\pard    - maximum budget\par
\pard 3. The UI creates a `Buyer` object.\par
\pard 4. Validation is performed.\par
\pard 5. Duplicate ID checks are performed.\par
\pard 6. If successful, the buyer is stored and displayed.\par
\pard \par
\pard\b 6.3 Matching workflow\b0\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. The user chooses a buyer or selects the option to generate all matches.\par
\pard 2. The system loops through farmers.\par
\pard 3. For each farmer, the system checks:\par
\pard    - is the crop the same?\par
\pard    - is the city the same?\par
\pard    - is the price within the buyer's budget?\par
\pard    - is quantity available greater than zero?\par
\pard 4. If compatible, the system calculates a match score.\par
\pard 5. A `MatchRecord` object is created.\par
\pard 6. All compatible matches are sorted by score.\par
\pard 7. The best matches are shown in the table and report area.\par
\pard \par
\pard\b 6.4 File workflow\b0\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. When the user clicks save, farmer data, buyer data, and match data are written to CSV files.\par
\pard 2. When the user clicks load, the system reads those files line by line.\par
\pard 3. CSV values are converted back into `Farmer` and `Buyer` objects.\par
\pard 4. If there is any invalid data, a custom exception is raised.\par
\pard 5. Backup and restore use object streams to serialize and deserialize the full state.\par
\pard \par
\par
