\pard\b\fs27 9. How the Matching Logic Works\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard The matching logic is kept simple so that it is easy to explain in class.\par
\pard \par
\pard The method `isCompatibleWith(Buyer buyer)` in `Farmer` checks:\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. buyer must not be null\par
\pard 2. crop type must match\par
\pard 3. city must match\par
\pard 4. price per unit must be less than or equal to buyer budget\par
\pard 5. quantity available must be greater than zero\par
\pard \par
\pard If all of these are true, the buyer and farmer are considered compatible.\par
\pard \par
\pard Then `calculateMatchScore(Buyer buyer)` gives a score:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? base score starts at `80`\par
\pard\li720 ? quantity closeness contributes up to `20`\par
\pard\li720 ? final score is rounded to 2 decimal places\par
\pard \par
\pard This creates a ranked recommendation system without unnecessary complexity.\par
\pard \par
\par
\pard \par
\pard\b\fs27 10. How Data Moves Through the System\b0\fs24\par
\pard \par
\pard The internal data flow of the project is:\par
\pard \par
\pard 1. UI accepts input\par
\pard 2. Input becomes an object\par
\pard 3. Object is validated\par
\pard 4. Manager stores object\par
\pard 5. Matching methods compare objects\par
\pard 6. Result becomes `MatchRecord`\par
\pard 7. Table and report show the result\par
\pard 8. File manager saves data\par
\pard \par
\pard This separation is important because it makes the code organized:\par
\pard \par
\pard\li720 ? UI handles presentation\par
\pard\li720 ? manager handles logic\par
\pard\li720 ? models hold data\par
\pard\li720 ? file manager handles storage\par
\pard\li720 ? utilities support the system\par
\pard \par
\par
